< Review>
Pretty disappointed with the customer service experience at the front desk. Although I live in Canada, I'm in the process of moving to SD for work and decided to try Crunch while here in San Diego for a few days. I asked if I could have a tour and asked if they provided a day pass to try out the facility while explaining my situation and the girl at the front said without hesitation "if you're not a resident it's $10". I said ok, no problem and paid. The conversation ended there. I had no idea about the gym, their offerings and even had to ask where the locker rooms were. I'm in the gym 5-6 times a week so it's important to me to be in a place I can call home but I won't be returning to a business that made me feel so dismissed. Gym is quite good, good size, good and clean equipment. Do better with people, you guys!< /Review>

This is because we choose quality over quantity. On this note, whenever a visitor come to our shop we provide an accurate estimate of the time of preparation before accepting the payment, this allow the visitor to decide whether to patiently wait or come back at a different time.\n\nOn the same note, we also suggest to preorder your meal for dine in or take out, we are actually the only restaurant in the south bay that provide this service and most of our visitors seems to appreciate this option. Food items that don\'t travel well like Cacio e Pepe Sauce, Carbonara and Mortazza pizza are actually available only for dine in.\n\nAs far as the rest of the items, after 20 minutes in the box, any pasta would get cold and when pasta gets cold, it releases starch, which ultimately result in what you have indicated to be a "pasta ball".\nFrom the description you have made, it sounds like your pasta was consumed past this time, and had we known that, we would have probably recommended our pasta and sauces  to cook at home instead. This is a solution mostly appreciate by visitors who will not consume pasta within the 20 minute time range.\n\nThe same occur with the pizza, although you can resolve this issue by reheating the pizza in any domestic pre-heated oven at 550 degrees for 3 minutes.\n\nIn addition to home made pasta, we are also one of the only five locations in the whole city of Los Angeles to offer Roman Style Pizza. A 72 hours temperature controlled matured pizza dough, that make a thick pizza fluffy and light in the inside and crisp on the outside. Roman Style Pizza is a type of pizza pretty popular in most Italian bakeries in Italy, often consumed as an full meal or simply as a snack. Most of our visitors find our pizza amongst the best in Southern California, however I realize that some people might prefer other types of pizza. At our Shop we offer Roman Style Pizza in six different versions, both by the slice or by the sheet. < review>
Combined review based on2 separate visits. It went from a 5 to a 1.

In 29 years living in the U.S., I‚Äôve never had a lasagna nearly as good as the one I had tonight (July 4th, 2019). Marco is a phenomenal chef and a great guy. His place is legit!

August 31, 2019:
I promised my son I was going to take him to Fatto a Mano to try the best lasagna. So we went last Saturday at 1120. Met with Marco and he did not recognize me. He was deep in the weeds, extremely busy and working by himself. He told us he ran out of lasagna, so we ordered the fettuccine bolognese and spaghetti carbonara. Marco was working by himself!!!! I felt so bad I was thinking I should get in there and help him out. He had 5 orders ahead of ours and we waited 45 minutes. The bolognese was good, but the carbonara was a huge disappointment, raw pasta, cold sauce, raw pancetta, watery and bland sauce. Right before we left, an employee shows up.

My experience went from a solid 5 stars in July, to a 1 star last week in August.

It‚Äôs pretty sad that you had to sacrifice quality like that Marco. And it can‚Äôt be healthy for you either. Next time, you should open later when you have the required help you need. You can‚Äôt run a kitchen and take orders by yourself and expect to put out a consistent, high quality product.< /review>

Extra Space on Ventura Blvd is superior.  First of all, even though they do not claim it has AC - it is always cool, even though it might be 99 degrees outside, it is a cool 69 inside.  This is very important for companies like me who store tapes that cannot get too hot.  Must be because it is sort of built into the hill.  The guy who runs it is Tom. Mark McCaffrey< /user_name>
< date>
1401601002213<//date>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Review>
It's the little things that matter to me in having a storage space.  At this one the lighting is perfect, for example.  It lasts a long time and if it goes out, you just have to wave your hand in the air.  It's a clean place, the carts are sturdier than those I've seen at other places, the doors to the units are adequately wide, the floors are polished and the freight elevator is big enough to bring a couple of circus horses into.  It's well-tended, has good parking space considering it's in a crowded part of LA, and the management is friendly and helpful.  The only thing I might wish could be improved is the height and location of the keypad to let yourself in.  You can't use it from the driver's seat of your vehicle, but instead have to get out, punch in your code, then hop back into your car or truck while the gate opens. This is a minor hassle, I suppose, in what is in general an ideal storage facility.</Review>

None</Pictures>

< Review>
Their produce is compatible with the big guys and you can fill your water jugs up here also. There's also a meat department where you can buy carnitas on the weekends and a prepared food department where you can order up a torta or bionico/fruit bowl or an agua. This store is very popular with the locals. Also on the weekends they set up a taco stand in front of the store.</Review>

< Text>
I just had the #7 meal (chicken sandwich) & ordered at the walk-up window. The food was prepared quickly and (even though I waited till I was home) it was very tasty. The fries always seem to be freshly cooked, as well. My only complaint, and it's A BIG ONE: this is the only restaurant available to pedestrians late night (till 3am every night), except Subway down the street, and they randomly close the walk-up but serve the lazy people driving at 2am for fast food. I know that lately it's been due to lack of personnel present for their shift, but you don't close the walkup. The cars can go anywhere easily - people on foot can't.< /Text>

1594619168388<//time>
<rate>3</rate>< text>
It's okay!

The drive thru went into the street, and the wait time was long. About 10 minutes? 10 minutes to order, and then another 10 waiting for my food.

The soda was flat, and they had to check with me at the window what my order was, but at least they're making sure I don't leave without my food, so I greatly appreciate it!

The burger was still hot and delicious! I ordered the Buford, and it was just what I wanted!

The fries were soft, lukewarm, and kind of average tasting. They look really good with all that spice on em, but the crunch isn't satisfying, and the flavor is kind of bland.

I ordered mozzarella sticks, but they were out. I don't blame them, though, cause I came in at 9 pm xD

I also ordered the garlic chicken wings, which were SO good, the sauce actually tastes like it's made with real garlic, but the packaging is leaky. My home is only 10 minutes away, but the bottom of the bag was soaked with greasy sauce from the wings, and now I have this majorly huge, garlic-smelling grease stain on the front passenger seat of my car :/

It's definitely a place I'll revisit, but I don't think it's at the top of my list.< /text>

<rate>5<//rate><review>It is a rarity that I stop in at a Rally's or Checkers. That very much is true. Another truth is that there are not many of them. That is perfectly fine by me, and it makes each visit worthwhile. I had the baconzilla combo. Bacon and cheese and the beef patty and the bun were very much as I remembered the last time I had it. Very straightforward. All stacked in a choreographed pile of goodness. My burger this time was no different. It had a good amount of bacon which provided the right amount of saltiness to compliment the beef patties and the melted cheese. The bacon had a good amount of crispiness too. The seasoned fries are a step above any other fast food restaurant standard french fries. Of course if you prefer seasoned fries. Which I do, and mine were done perfectly. I also had a strawberry smoothie that was very..... smooth with just the right amount of sweetness. Rally's and Checker's offer soft serve and other dessert items too. So on hot days it is worth checking out. Outside seating is only available. It is a very modern location and parking is available and well lit.</review><pictures>None< /pictures><Response>None<//Response>< gmap_id>

<text>I've been a big fan of Rally's since I was teenager about 26 summers ago, so was glad to hear this Rally's was close to us. Drive Thru is poorly designed. Only 3 cars fit from the ordering speaker to the drive up window. That coupled with very, very (almost dmv'esque) slow and "don't bother me service" , we ended with a 26 minute wait start to finish as car #5 in the drive thru. Probably should give 2 Stars but in all honesty for the price the food was pretty good, an excellent value. This Rally's has alot of potential, with the right manager who can keep the employees happy, motivated and productive. Could really be an asset to helping the local community. Will come back again and maybe order at pick up window and see what happens. Was also very clean and well maintained on the outside at least.</text></record></dataset><record>
